column9: Flying over southern tip of Greenland
column16: Image made using my iPhone 14 Pro, main camera, out the port side window of an airplane (flight between Boston and Keflavik in Iceland). Time given is east coast time, not local (my phone was in airplane mode). I think I used Portrait mode, which helped the camera focus on the cloud and not the dirt on the plane window. I'm estimating location by two things: i was able to take a picture of the plane's location on the seat back screen at 11:54 pm on 8/3/2025, which showed the plane just west of the south coast of Greenland. 20 minutes later at the time I took this image, I'm guessing we were west of that location.

column9: Flying over southern tip of Greenland
column16: I took image with my iPhone 14 pro, using the main camera, out the plane's window. Time is east coast time, I think, not local (I had my phone in airplane mode). I had to play around with image type to get camera not to focus on dirt on the window. I think Portrait mode is what was most successful.

This photo was taken with a Pixel 7 Pro on 8/4/25 @ 12:12 am. The sky was clear, noise levels were very minimal and the temperature was around 70°F . The cloud appeared after an incident I witnessed that occurred while sitting outside on my back porch approximately at 12:00 AM facing south . I am located just slightly north west from Ontario Intl Airport. The night was very quiet when  I began to hear a loud screeching sound. My first thought was that it was just the cats fighting. That was until I noticed the sound rapidly getting louder and closer. Right when it got the loudest all of a sudden  the whole sky lit up so bright like day time. Then, immediately followed the loudest boom I've ever heard. This was most definitely  not a gun shot or firework. The sound was heard as far as at least 15 miles away. From the time I witnessed the sky light up, the loud boom, getting to my front porch and taking the photo was approximately 3 minutes. I was facing East and the cloud was coming from the south moving north very slowly.

This display had reports come in on Facebook / online around midnight but I did not observe until the pre-dawn hours, thinking it would ahve been too low to the horizon or too dark on the south coast of England. At 03:45 there was a nice show - quite widespread although not that bright (may have been trying to compete with the twilight by that time). An enjoyable show, and as it was better than expected, a lovely surprise!

The noctilucent clouds were very bright with some cirrus and a few lower altitude clouds thrown in. I observed these from about 11:15 pm MDT on June 29 to about 12:30 am MDT on June 30.  The NLCs had a wave-lake structure to them and appeared to move slowly from east to west.  The other clouds were more random in shape and moved a little quicker from west to east.
Photographed with a Canon EOS T5i, Canon 18-55 @25mm, f5.6, 0.7 seconds @ISO1600.

column16: The clouds were visible from late 29 June 2025 till dawn on 30 June 2025. The image here, taken at 11:53 PM local time, looks NNW. In the morning a lot of wavelets developed at the fringe of the clouds in N to NNE. Lumix FZ2000 f/4 0.62 sec ISO-1600

column9: North Atlantic, southwest of Keflavik Airport, Iceland
column16: I used an iPhone 11Pro and took the image out the plane's window. I was on a flight from Boston's Logan airport to Iceland's Keflavik airport. Time given is Boston time, I'm not sure what local time it was, but it was just before dawn (flight landed ~6 am at Keflavik, I think?). I don't have exact location data, I've provided an estimate.

column9: N. Atlantic, en route between Boston, MA and Keflavik, Iceland
column16: I used an Apple 1Phone 11Pro to take this image out the window of an airplane. Best as I can remember, it was ~1 hour out of the Keflavik airport on Iceland, on a flight from Boston's Logan airport.
Complementary observation of previous day, same location and time but no NCs. Some cirrus clouds.

Camera: Canon EOS 1300D. Observed for twenty minutes from 0216 to 0236, present for longer. Comet NEOWISE is in the image (upper left). Heading approximately north

NLCs were observed low on the northern horizon from about 11:30 PM, July 7, 2018 until they faded at about 00:10 AM, July 8, 2018.  The sky was otherwise mostly cloudless. This image was taken at 11:39 PM on July 7, 2018. Camera used was Canon EOS T5i, 18-55mm lens at 30mm, f/8, ISO-1600, 1.3s exposure.
Nikon D300, f=28 mm at f/2.8 for 1/4 s. Observed by Joseph A Shaw. This is a test image.
